data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages (just "Expected: True, Actual: False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Specialized assertions = clear failure messages
    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));    // no built-in "all match" assertion, IsTrue is fine here
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your code | Better alternative | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure says "Expected: 3, Actual: N" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Failure says "value was null" |

Other useful collection assertions in MSTest 3.x+:
- **`Assert.Contains(item, collection)`** — item exists
- **`Assert.DoesNotContain(item, collection)`** — item absent
- **`Assert.ContainsSingle(collection)`** — exactly one element, returns it
- **`Assert.IsEmpty(collection)`** — collection is empty
